transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for having me. I'm glad to be part of this interview. I'm ready for your questions.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Sure! As I mentioned, my name is Abigail, and I'm 38 years old. I live in urban Dallas, where I work as a social worker. I have a master's degree, and I've been in my field for several years now, which I find very rewarding. I'm divorced, and I have two children from my previous marriage. They keep me quite busy! I try to maintain a balance between my professional life and my responsibilities as a mother. Health-wise, I consider myself moderately health-conscious; I exercise occasionally and try to eat well, although I admit life can get hectic at times. I'm currently using an intrauterine device for contraception since I’m not planning on having any more children. Overall, I feel grateful for my good healthcare access through my employer's insurance, which makes it easier for me to manage my health.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Of course. I first learned I was pregnant with my first child when I was 28 years old. I remember it vividly; I took a home pregnancy test after feeling a bit off for a few days, and when it came back positive, I was both excited and a little nervous. My first pregnancy was pretty straightforward, and I had an uncomplicated vaginal delivery. I had my second child about two years later, and the experience was similar. I felt prepared and supported, especially with the resources available to me through my healthcare plan.

After my second child, I made the decision to have an elective abortion, which was a tough choice but one that I felt was right for my circumstances at the time. It was an experience that I approached thoughtfully, and I was grateful for the care I received.

Overall, my pregnancies were positive experiences, and I felt well-supported by my healthcare providers during that time. Would you like to know more about my prenatal care experiences or anything specific related to my pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I first sought prenatal care early in my first pregnancy, around the 8-week mark. I scheduled my appointment with my OB-GYN right after I confirmed my pregnancy with the home test. The experience was quite positive. My doctor was very welcoming and took the time to answer all my questions, which helped ease my nerves. 

During that initial visit, we discussed my medical history, and they conducted the necessary tests to ensure everything was progressing well. I appreciated the thoroughness of the prenatal care process, including regular check-ups and ultrasounds. It made me feel reassured about my health and my baby’s development. 

With my second pregnancy, I sought care just as early, and the experience was similar. I felt like I was in good hands and had access to all the resources I needed. 

Would you like to know more about the types of care I received or any specific aspects of the prenatal visits?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I received my prenatal care from an OB-GYN who was affiliated with a local hospital. I found her to be very knowledgeable and compassionate, which made a significant difference in my experience. From the very first visit, she made me feel comfortable and safe, which is crucial during such an important time. 

We developed a good rapport over my pregnancies; I felt like I could trust her completely. She was always open to discussing any concerns I had, whether they were about my health, the baby's development, or even my emotional well-being during pregnancy. I appreciated the fact that she took the time to listen, and she never rushed through appointments. I think that relationship helped me feel more empowered and informed as a mother.

During my visits, she always encouraged me to ask questions, which I did, especially about nutrition and exercise during pregnancy. I also appreciated how she explained the purpose of each test and what to expect at each stage of my pregnancy. It felt like a partnership, and I think that really contributed to my positive experiences.

Would you like to know more about the specific types of prenatal care I received or any challenges I faced during that time?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Absolutely. During my pregnancies, I typically had prenatal appointments every four weeks during the first trimester. As I moved into the second trimester, those appointments became every two weeks, and then weekly as I approached my due date. 

A typical visit would start with me checking in at the front desk and then being taken to an examination room. The nurse would first take my vital signs, including my weight and blood pressure. After that, I would meet with my OB-GYN for a more in-depth discussion. 

My doctor would usually begin by asking how I was feeling, both physically and emotionally. This was important to me, as I wanted to ensure I was taking care of my mental health during pregnancy. Then, we would review any symptoms I was experiencing or any questions I had. 

Next, there would often be a physical examination, which included listening to the baby's heartbeat with a Doppler, measuring my belly for growth, and discussing any necessary lab tests or ultrasounds. I really appreciated the time my doctor took to explain what they were doing, which made me feel more engaged in the process.

Sometimes, we would also discuss nutrition and exercise recommendations based on where I was in my pregnancy. I found that those conversations helped me feel more connected to the experience and empowered to make healthy choices for myself and my baby.

After everything, we would wrap up by discussing my next appointment and any follow-up care needed. Overall, I appreciated the structure of the visits and the thoroughness of the care I received. 

Is there anything specific about the appointments or care processes that you would like to know more about?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I was fortunate not to experience any significant health concerns or complications. Both of my pregnancies were relatively uncomplicated, which I was very grateful for. I did have some common discomforts, like morning sickness in the early weeks and some back pain later on, but nothing that required medical intervention.

I was proactive about my health, and I think that helped. I followed my doctor's advice regarding nutrition, exercise, and prenatal vitamins. Additionally, I made sure to attend all my scheduled appointments, which allowed my healthcare provider to monitor my progress closely.

The only ongoing health issue I've dealt with outside of pregnancy is chronic sinusitis, which can sometimes flare up, but it didn't have any impact on my pregnancies. My healthcare team was always attentive to my overall health, and I felt supported in managing any minor issues.

If you’d like, I can share more about how I managed my overall wellbeing during pregnancy or how my experiences may have influenced my approach to maternal health.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Currently, I take a few medications and supplements. For my chronic sinusitis, I occasionally use a nasal corticosteroid spray to help manage my symptoms, especially during allergy seasons when my sinus issues tend to flare up. I also take a daily multivitamin, which I started during my pregnancies and have continued since then, as I believe it's beneficial for my overall health.

Additionally, I take vitamin D supplements, especially since I work indoors most of the day and don’t get as much sunlight as I’d like. I try to focus on maintaining a balanced diet, but I find that these supplements help fill in any gaps.

It’s been a while since I've had a medication review, so I know I should probably schedule one to ensure everything is still appropriate and that there are no interactions I need to be aware of. 

Do you have any specific questions about these medications or supplements, or would you like to know more about how I manage my health overall?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I was quite mindful of my diet and nutrition. I understood how important it was to fuel my body properly for both my health and the growing baby. I focused on a balanced diet that included a variety of food groups. 

I made sure to consume plenty of fruits and vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. For example, I included foods like leafy greens, berries, whole grain bread, chicken, fish, and nuts in my meals. I also paid attention to hydration, making sure to drink plenty of water throughout the day.

At the beginning of each pregnancy, I was careful to include foods rich in folate, like beans and fortified cereals, to support fetal development. I also made it a point to take my prenatal vitamins consistently, as I knew they contained essential nutrients like iron and DHA that are crucial during pregnancy.

I did have some cravings during both pregnancies, particularly for carbohydrates and dairy, but I tried to balance those with healthier options. I also made sure to limit my intake of processed foods, sugary snacks, and caffeine, as my doctor recommended.

Throughout my pregnancies, my healthcare provider provided me with guidance on nutrition and offered suggestions tailored to my specific needs. I appreciated those conversations because they helped me feel more confident in my choices.

If you’re interested, I can elaborate more on how my dietary choices evolved during my pregnancies or how I adapted my nutrition postpartum.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I experienced a range of emotions, which I think is quite normal. Initially, there was a lot of excitement and anticipation, especially when I first learned I was pregnant. However, I also had moments of anxiety and uncertainty, particularly as I navigated the changes in my body and the responsibilities of becoming a mother.

I made a conscious effort to stay in tune with my emotions throughout both pregnancies. I found that talking about my feelings with my healthcare provider was incredibly helpful. She encouraged open discussions about not just my physical health, but also my mental and emotional well-being. I appreciated that she validated my feelings and offered coping strategies when I expressed any worries or stress.

I did experience some mood swings, which I learned can be common due to hormonal changes. I tried to practice self-care by engaging in activities that helped me relax, such as going for walks, practicing mindfulness, and spending time with supportive friends and family. 

Support from my social network was crucial; I leaned on friends who had been through similar experiences, and they provided me with comfort and perspective. I also made time for myself, which I think was important in maintaining my emotional balance.

Overall, I felt that being proactive about my emotional health made a positive difference in my pregnancies. If you'd like, I can share more about specific strategies I used to manage my emotions or how I approached mental health postpartum.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I was fortunate to have a strong support network. My family and friends played a significant role in helping me navigate the journey of motherhood. My parents were incredibly supportive and always made themselves available to help with my children, especially when I needed a break or had appointments. They are just a short drive away, which made it easy for them to step in when needed.

My close friends, many of whom are mothers themselves, were also a great source of support. They shared their experiences and offered advice, which helped me feel less alone in my journey. We often met up to discuss parenting challenges, and it was comforting to know that others were going through similar experiences. 

In addition to my personal network, I also found support through my colleagues at work. As a social worker, I interacted with many parents and families in my role, and I learned a lot from their stories. Some even became informal mentors to me, sharing their insights and coping strategies for managing work-life balance while raising children.

Lastly, my healthcare provider was a vital part of my support system. She not only addressed my medical needs but also recognized the importance of emotional support during pregnancy. She encouraged me to reach out when I felt overwhelmed, and that made a significant difference.

Overall, I believe that having a strong support network contributed to my positive experiences during pregnancy. If you're interested, I can elaborate on how I balanced support from different sources or how my network evolved as I transitioned into motherhood.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Absolutely, I did think about my birth plan for both of my pregnancies, and I had specific preferences for delivery that I communicated with my healthcare provider. 

For both of my uncomplicated vaginal deliveries, I wanted to maintain a natural approach without unnecessary interventions, as long as everything was progressing normally. I appreciated the idea of being able to move around during labor and having the option for different positions to help with comfort and progress. 

I also expressed my desire to have continuous support during labor, whether from my partner, family, or a doula. I believed that having familiar faces around would help create a calming environment. I wanted to minimize stress and focus on the moment.

Pain management was another aspect I considered. I planned to start with non-medical pain relief methods, like breathing techniques and movement, and only consider epidurals or other medications if absolutely necessary. I felt it was important to be flexible, as I understood that labor can be unpredictable.

Skin-to-skin contact immediately after birth was a priority for me. I wanted to have that bonding experience with my baby right away, as I knew it could enhance the early connection and support breastfeeding. 

In terms of postpartum care, I hoped to have a supportive environment where I could initiate breastfeeding immediately and receive help with any challenges that might arise.

Overall, I felt that having a clear birth plan, while remaining open to adjustments based on how things unfolded, helped me feel more prepared and empowered. If you would like to know more about my experiences during delivery or how my birth plans evolved, just let me know!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I used a combination of sources to learn about pregnancy and childbirth. One of the first places I turned to was my OB-GYN. She provided me with a wealth of information during my prenatal visits, including brochures and recommendations for books and websites that were reputable. I appreciated her guidance, as she always directed me to evidence-based resources.

I also read several popular pregnancy books that covered everything from prenatal development to childbirth techniques. Some of my favorites included "What to Expect When You're Expecting" and "The Mayo Clinic Guide to a Healthy Pregnancy." These books helped me understand what to expect at each stage of pregnancy and offered tips for self-care and preparation for labor.

Additionally, I explored online resources and forums for expecting mothers, such as BabyCenter and What to Expect. These platforms allowed me to connect with other moms-to-be and share experiences, which was comforting. I found it helpful to read personal stories and advice from others who were going through similar journeys.

I also attended a few prenatal classes offered through my hospital, which covered childbirth, breastfeeding, and newborn care. These classes provided hands-on learning and an opportunity to ask questions in a supportive environment. I found the group discussions to be particularly beneficial, as they allowed me to connect with other expectant parents.

Lastly, I relied on recommendations from friends and family who had been through pregnancy and childbirth. Their personal insights and experiences were invaluable, and I often turned to them for support and advice.

Overall, I felt that using a mix of professional guidance, literature, online resources, and personal connections helped me feel well-informed and prepared for my pregnancies. If you're interested, I can share more about any specific resources I found particularly useful or how my views on certain topics evolved over time.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I took a proactive approach to manage the financial aspects and prepare for the arrival of my babies. Since I have good healthcare access through my employer's insurance plan, I felt more secure knowing that many of my prenatal visits, tests, and deliveries would be covered. I made sure to familiarize myself with my insurance benefits to understand what was included and what out-of-pocket expenses I might expect.

I also created a budget to account for any additional costs associated with having a baby, such as maternity clothes, baby gear, and childcare. I started saving early on to prepare for these expenses, and I focused on purchasing essential items rather than going overboard on non-essentials. For instance, I prioritized items like a crib, car seat, and stroller, while waiting to buy other things until I had a better sense of what I really needed once the baby arrived.

In addition to budgeting, I explored various resources for financial assistance and discounts. I found local programs in Dallas that offered support for new parents, including free parenting classes and community resources for baby supplies. I also took advantage of sales and clearance events to purchase baby items at a lower cost.

During both pregnancies, I communicated openly with my ex-husband about our financial responsibilities and made sure we were on the same page regarding budgeting for the new baby. This collaboration helped ease any stress related to finances and allowed us to focus more on preparing for our growing family.

Lastly, I made a point to educate myself on the potential costs associated with childbirth and postpartum care. I asked my healthcare provider about expected expenses and any potential financial planning strategies that could help me navigate the process.

Overall, I felt that being organized and informed about the financial aspects of pregnancy helped reduce anxiety and allowed me to focus more on the joy of bringing a new life into the world. If you’d like, I can share more about specific budgeting strategies I used or how I prepared financially for postpartum care.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I found that my work situation was impacted in several ways, but overall, I was fortunate to have a supportive work environment as a social worker. Initially, when I learned I was pregnant, I was a bit apprehensive about how to manage my responsibilities at work while also preparing for a baby. However, I communicated openly with my supervisor about my pregnancy, which helped set the stage for a smooth transition.

I continued to work full-time throughout both pregnancies, and I made sure to prioritize self-care to manage my energy levels. Thankfully, my employer offered flexible working hours, which allowed me to adjust my schedule as needed, especially during the later stages of pregnancy when I experienced fatigue. I found it helpful to take short breaks throughout the day, especially during client meetings or casework, to recharge and stay focused.

In terms of my workload, I was mindful of balancing my responsibilities, and I sometimes delegated tasks to my colleagues when it became overwhelming. I felt supported by my team, and they were understanding of my situation, which made a significant difference in how I managed my work-life balance.

As I approached my due dates, I planned for maternity leave well in advance. I consulted with HR to understand my benefits and the process for taking leave, which helped me feel prepared. I also took time to ensure that my cases were transitioned smoothly to colleagues so that my absence wouldn't create undue stress on my team.

I did experience some physical discomfort during my pregnancies, like back pain, which required me to adjust how I sat at my desk or engaged with clients. Overall, I was able to maintain a good level of productivity, but I also learned to listen to my body and prioritize my health when necessary.

After the births, I took the allotted maternity leave to bond with my babies and recover, which I felt was essential. Returning to work afterward was an adjustment, but I was grateful for the support of my employer and colleagues during that transition.

If you’re interested, I can share more about how I navigated specific challenges at work or how my experiences shaped my approach to balancing motherhood and my career.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
During my pregnancies, I definitely thought about the postpartum period and made plans to ensure I was prepared for the transition after the baby arrived. I understood that the postpartum phase could come with its own set of challenges, both physically and emotionally, so I wanted to be proactive.

First and foremost, I planned for rest and recovery. I knew that childbirth could be exhausting, and I wanted to give myself the time and space to heal. I arranged for support from my parents and close friends, who offered to help with household tasks and care for my older children during that initial period. Having that support network in place made me feel more at ease about managing everything.

I also focused on establishing a routine that would include time for self-care. I planned to set aside moments for myself, whether it was taking a short walk, practicing mindfulness, or simply enjoying a quiet cup of tea. I recognized the importance of mental health during the postpartum period, so I aimed to stay connected with my support network and reach out when I needed assistance or someone to talk to.

Additionally, I made a plan for breastfeeding, as I wanted to nurse my baby if possible. I attended breastfeeding classes during my pregnancy, which helped me feel more prepared for any challenges that might arise. I also reached out to a lactation consultant in advance to have support readily available if I needed it after the baby was born.

Financially, I considered the costs associated with postpartum care, such as follow-up appointments, any medications I might need, and baby supplies. I budgeted for these expenses and ensured I had the necessary items, like nursing bras and postpartum recovery products, ready to go.

Overall, I wanted to create a balanced plan that considered my physical recovery, emotional well-being, and the needs of my family. I felt that being prepared would help me navigate the postpartum period more smoothly. If you'd like, I can share more about specific strategies I planned to implement or how I approached postpartum care after my first two pregnancies.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
